lesion is a 3 mm, bright red, dome-shaped papule that blanches with pressure (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Basal cell carcinoma","Melanoma","Cherry angioma","Pyogenic granuloma","Squamous cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe description of a less than one centimeter, bright red, dome-shaped capillary papule that blanches with pressure is characteristic of a \u003Cstrong\u003Echerry angioma - \u003C/strong\u003Ealso known as Campbell de Morgan spots. When they are thrombosed, they may appear dark purple in colour.  These benign vascular lesions are common in adults, especially those over 40 years old, and tend to increase in number with age though it can occur in children more rarely (infantile haemangioma or strawberry naevus). Unlike infantile haemangiomas, adult cherry angiomas do not tend to self-resolve.  Cherry angiomas occur anywhere on the body and may be flat, but are most common on the trunk and proximal extremities.  They are less commonly found on the palms, feet or mucous membranes but can still occur on these sites such as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMelanoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as an irregularly shaped, asymmetrical lesion with variable pigmentation from skin-coloured, red or black. However, melanoma lesions would not blanch with pressure as are not capillary papules. While melanoma can occur on the lips, it is not consistent with the description provided in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epyogenic granuloma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rapidly growing vascular lesion that often develops after minor trauma. While it can appear similar to a cherry angioma, pyogenic granulomas tend to be larger, friable, and prone to bleeding. They are also less common in older adults compared to cherry angiomas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E (BCC) is the most common type of skin cancer and can occur on the lips. However, BCCs typically present as pearly, flesh-colored or pink bumps, often with a central depression or ulceration. They do not match the bright red appearance or lack of ulceration described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E (SCC) can also occur on the lips, especially the lower lip. SCCs usually appear as firm, red, scaly patches or papules that may ulcerate. They also would not blanch with pressure as the lesion does in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECherry angiomas are generally harmless and do not require treatment unless they bleed frequently or cause cosmetic concerns. They are not pre-malignant.  If treatment is desired, options include electrocautery, cryotherapy, or laser therapy. It\u0027s important to differentiate cherry angiomas from other vascular lesions or skin cancers to ensure appropriate management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cherry angiomas are benign vascular lesions that commonly appear with age.","Most cherry angiomas do not require treatment unless they bleed or cause cosmetic concerns."],"references":["Oakley A. Cherry angioma. In: DermNetNZ [online]. 2020. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/cherry-angioma","Cherry Angiomas. In: The Autraliasian College of Dermatologists A-Z of Skin [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.dermcoll.edu.au/atoz/cherry-angiomas/","Pastor-Tom\u00e1s N, Ba\u00f1uls J, Nagore E. [Translated article] Clinical Relevance of Cherry Angiomas. Actas Dermo-Sifiliogr\u00e1ficas. 2023;114(3):T240-T6. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0001731023000479"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39072"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14003"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20914"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20914"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hWvmY9F3KA1eqr9iBlCITOzU7MXC70.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hWvmY9F3KA1eqr9iBlCITOzU7MXC70.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39072"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-23T12:51:25+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T12:52:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6652"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53613"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Onl